/*
ğŸ§© Problem: Minimum Distance Between Equal Triplets

You are given an integer array nums.
Find the minimum total distance between three equal elements (nums[i] == nums[j] == nums[k]) such that i < j < k.

The total distance is defined as:
    (j - i) + (k - j) + (k - i)

If no such triplet exists, return -1.

---------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ§  Example:

Input:
nums = [1, 2, 1, 2, 1]

Output:
6

Explanation:
Triplet of 1 occurs at indices (0, 2, 4)
Distance = (2 - 0) + (4 - 2) + (4 - 0) = 6
---------------------------------------------------------
âš™ï¸ Approach:

- Iterate through all possible triplets (i, j, k) such that i < j < k.
- Check if all three elements are equal.
- Compute total distance and keep track of the minimum found.
- Return -1 if no valid triplet exists.

---------------------------------------------------------
â±ï¸ Complexity Analysis:

Time Complexity:  O(nÂ³)
Space Complexity: O(1)
---------------------------------------------------------
*/

class Solution {
    public int minimumDistance(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int ans = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                for (int k = j + 1; k < n; k++) {
                    if (nums[i] == nums[j] && nums[j] == nums[k]) {
                        int dis = (j - i) + (k - j) + (k - i);
                        ans = Math.min(ans, dis);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return ans == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : ans;
    }
}

/*
ğŸ§® Example Walkthrough:
nums = [3, 1, 3, 3]
Triplet (0, 2, 3) => Distance = (2 - 0) + (3 - 2) + (3 - 0) = 6
Output = 6
---------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ Summary:
âœ”ï¸ Simple brute-force solution
âœ”ï¸ Works for small arrays
âœ”ï¸ Can be optimized using index tracking or hashing if needed
*/
